      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Long-Tenanted Property in Brisbane: Presentation, Disclosure and Buyer Expectations
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When a property has been tenanted for years, the sale process looks different. Here's what Brisbane sellers need to know about tenant rights, disclosure obligations, and how to position the property for the right buyer pool.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A property that has been tenanted for five, eight or ten years presents a different set of challenges to a sale than an owner-occupied home or a freshly renovated investment. The tenant has made it their home. The wear and tear reflects years of everyday living. The relationship between owner and tenant may be warm and long-standing, which can make the negotiation around access and presentation genuinely difficult. And the buyer pool, while real, is different in composition and in expectation to the one an owner-occupier home attracts.</p>

      <p>None of these challenges make a long-tenanted property unsaleable. Many achieve strong results. But they do require a different approach from the vendor, the agent and the tenant than a standard listing demands. Getting that approach right from the outset avoids the problems that most commonly derail these campaigns: a tenant who feels blindsided, a buyer who walks after the building inspection, or a disclosure issue that surfaces late in the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why long-tenancy properties present unique challenges</h2>
      <p>The most immediate issue is presentation. A tenant who has lived in a property for a decade has accumulated furniture, personal belongings and domestic clutter that a short-term tenant or an owner preparing for sale would not have. The garden may be in a state that reflects a rental arrangement rather than owner-occupier pride. Walls, carpets and fittings show wear that accumulates gradually and becomes normalised by the tenant but registers strongly in photographs and at open homes.</p>

      <p>Beyond the physical state of the property, there is often an emotional dimension. Long-term tenants frequently feel a strong connection to the property. They may have raised children there, or they may be elderly and have few realistic options for relocation. A vendor who handles this badly by announcing the sale abruptly or by allowing the agent to communicate with the tenant without care will often find that the tenant becomes uncooperative at exactly the point when cooperation is most needed: during the inspection and styling phase of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Reluctance to allow frequent access for open homes and private inspections is a common friction point. Under Queensland law, a tenant must be given reasonable notice of entry for inspections, and the right to quiet enjoyment is protected. A tenant who is upset about the sale has every right to make access difficult within the bounds of the legislation, and some will do exactly that.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenant rights under Queensland law during the sale process</h2>
      <p>Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (Queensland), a landlord selling a property must give the tenant proper notice and comply with strict rules around entry. For open homes and inspections during a sale campaign, the agent must give the tenant at least 24 hours written notice for a routine entry, and no more than two inspections per week are permitted without the tenant's agreement. The tenant does not have to vacate during open homes.</p>

      <p>If the property is sold to an owner-occupier and the existing tenancy is periodic (month to month), the new owner can give the tenant a notice to leave, but must provide at least four weeks notice after settlement. If the tenancy is fixed-term, the tenant has the right to remain until the end of that term regardless of the sale, unless there is a specific clause in the lease addressing this.</p>

      <p>Disclosure obligations are significant. Buyers are entitled to know the terms of the existing tenancy before they exchange contracts. This includes the current rent, the bond amount, whether the lease is fixed-term or periodic, and the expiry date of any fixed term. A vendor cannot misrepresent the tenancy status or withhold material information about the lease.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing the tenant relationship professionally</h2>
      <p>The most effective approach is to bring the tenant into the conversation early and treat them with genuine respect. A landlord who personally explains the decision to sell, acknowledges the inconvenience, and asks for the tenant's cooperation rather than demanding it will almost always get a better response than one who sends a formal letter via the property manager and leaves the tenant to hear the news impersonally.</p>

      <p>A practical consideration: some vendors offer their tenant a modest incentive for cooperation during the campaign, such as a temporary rent reduction or a contribution toward moving costs. This is not a legal requirement and should be weighed against the overall campaign budget, but where the tenant relationship is strained or where the inspection program is intensive, it can convert an uncooperative tenant into a cooperative one and is often worth the cost.</p>

      <p>The property manager, if there is one, should be briefed carefully on how to communicate with the tenant throughout the campaign. The agent managing the sale should be introduced to the tenant early and should treat every interaction with the tenant as consequential. A tenant who feels respected is far more likely to allow flexible inspection times, to tidy the property before open homes, and to be cooperative with buyers during the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether vacant possession is worth waiting for</h2>
      <p>This question comes up in most long-tenancy sale discussions and the answer depends on your specific situation. Vacant possession gives you full control over presentation and styling, opens the property to owner-occupier buyers without condition, and removes the access friction of the inspection program. For properties in suburbs with strong owner-occupier demand, particularly family homes in Brisbane's inner east, the premium available to a vacant, well-styled property compared to a tenanted one can be meaningful.</p>

      <p>The cost of waiting, however, is real. If you have to give the tenant notice and then wait for them to vacate, you may be looking at six to ten weeks before you can begin the styling and preparation process. Add the campaign itself and you are potentially looking at four to five months from the decision to sell to exchange. During that time you are holding the asset, paying rates and insurance, and potentially foregoing rental income if the property sits vacant after the tenant leaves but before sale.</p>

      <p>A useful middle path is to sell with vacant possession as a condition of settlement, where the contract provides for the tenant to have vacated by a specified date. This gives buyers the confidence of eventually owning an untenanted property while allowing the campaign to proceed with the tenant still in place. Your solicitor can advise on how to structure this correctly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer pool differences for long-tenanted properties</h2>
      <p>A tenanted investment property attracts a different buyer composition than an owner-occupier home. The primary buyers are other investors, who will evaluate the property on its rental yield, its capital growth prospects, and its condition relative to the asking price. Owner-occupiers are typically less interested in purchasing with a sitting tenant, particularly one on a fixed-term lease that extends for months past settlement.</p>

      <p>This matters for marketing and pricing strategy. An agent who pitches a long-tenanted property primarily at the owner-occupier market, or who prices it expecting owner-occupier demand to drive the result, is likely to be disappointed. The investor market is active and well-informed. Investors will scrutinise the current rent relative to market rent, the condition of the property, and the remaining lease term. They will discount for presentation issues, for deferred maintenance, and for the inconvenience of purchasing a property that requires attention before it can be re-let at market rent.</p>

      <p>An honest, transparent campaign that presents the property accurately, discloses the tenancy details in full, and targets the investor buyer pool directly will consistently outperform a campaign that tries to blur the tenancy reality in hopes of attracting owner-occupier interest that will not materialise.</p>

